      <lg type="edition">
<l>meṉpālā ṉuṭaṉaṇaii</l>
<l>vañcikōṭ ṭuṟaṅkunārai</l>
<l>yaṟaikarumpiṉ pūvaruntum</l>
<l>vaṉpālāṟ karuṅkālvarakiṉ</l>
<l><gap quantity="52" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>vaṅkaṭ kuṟumuyal veruva vayala</l>
<l>karuṅkōṭ ṭiruppaip pūvuṟaik kuntu</l>
<l>viḻaviṉ ṟāyiṉu muḻavar maṇṭai</l>
<l>yiruṅkeṭiṟṟu micaiyoṭu pūṅkaḷ vaikuntu</l>
<l><gap quantity="39" reason="lost" unit="character"/> tuṇaiyēm peruma</l>
<l>nelleṉṉā poṉṉeṉṉā</l>
<l>kaṉaṟṟakkoṇṭa naṟaveṉṉā</l>
<l><gap quantity="17" reason="lost" unit="character"/> maṉaiyeṉṉā vavaipalavum</l>
<l>yāṉṟaṇṭavun tāṉṟaṇṭā</l>
<l>ṉiṇamperutta koḻuñcōṟṟiṭai</l>
<l>maṇṇāṇap pukaḻvēṭṭu</l>
<l>nīrnāṇa neyvaḻaṅkip</l>
<l>purantō ṉentai yāmalantolai<gap quantity="10" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>yaṉṉōṉai yuṭaiyē meṉpa<gap quantity="4" reason="lost" unit="character"/>vaṟaṭ</l>
<l>kiyāṇṭu niṟka veḷḷi māṇṭa</l>
<l>vuṇṭa naṉkalam peytu nuṭakkavun</l>
<l>tiṉṟa naṇpa lūṉṟōṇṭavum</l>
<l>vanta vaika lallatu</l>
<l>ceṉṟa vellaic celavaṟi yēṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In the soft soil, the egrets(?) that slumber,</l>
<l>huddling together on the branches of the mahua trees (1f.)</l>
<l>eat flowers of the hacked-off sugarcane.</l>
<l>In the hard soil, with black-stalked millet (4)</l>
<l>…………………………………….. (5)</l>
<l>so that the pretty-eyed little hares are frightened in the neighbourhood, (6)</l>
<l>flowers drip from black-branched mahua trees. (7)</l>
<l>Even though there is a festival today, the bowls of the ploughmen (8)</l>
<l>contain flowery toddy along with a dish of big Keṭiṟu fish. (9)</l>
<l>……………………. We are companions, of great man. (10)</l>
<l>Not considering paddy, not considering gold, (11)</l>
<l>not considering hot things, not considering liquors (12)</l>
<l>…………. not considering the house, those many things, (13)</l>
<l>when I am eager [for them], he will not stint. (14)</l>
<l>Into the fat rice enriched with fat, (15)</l>
<l>wanting fame that puts to shame the earth, (16)</l>
<l>giving ghee that put to shame the water, (17)</l>
<l>our father is the one who protects [us]. After having suffered … (18)</l>
<l>we [now] possess one like him, they say. … (19)</l>
<l>Let Venus stand wherever. (20a-c)</l>
<l>Expect of the day that comes (23)</l>
<l>[for us] to pour [and] wash the good vessels from which we eat glorious things (20d-21)</l>
<l>and to dig out meat [pieces] from between [our] teeth that have eaten, (22)</l>
<l>we won’t know of going [away] to the extent we went. (24)</l>
</lg>
